= The External Anomalies Phase

The External Anomalies Phase began in 2041 and ended in 2047. Earth scientists, intelligence agencies, and public bodies detected activity that no known state or natural process could explain.

During this period, no single event or discovery prompted concern. Instead, a pattern of low-level anomalies emerged independently across multiple domains. Astronomical observations recorded transient signals and spatial inconsistencies that did not correspond to natural phenomena or known artificial objects. Advances in observational resolution made these irregularities increasingly difficult to dismiss as instrumentation error or statistical noise.

In parallel, Earth-based research institutions identified unexplained discontinuities in long-term datasets related to materials science, energy modelling, and computational benchmarking. Certain theoretical constraints long treated as fixed appeared increasingly mismatched with observed edge-case results, though no reproducible mechanism could be identified within existing physical frameworks. These findings remained largely confined to specialist communities and were often attributed to modelling artefacts or unresolved methodological issues.

Intelligence and security agencies found a separate social pattern. A small group left work, science, finance, and public institutions without signs of distress or crime. Each case looked ordinary on its own. The combined pattern led to quiet internal reviews.

Throughout this phase, no unified theory linked these observations. Each domain treated its findings in isolation, and no public-facing acknowledgment was made. Where anomalies were recognised internally, they were typically classified as unresolved, pending further data. The absence of overt threat indicators or hostile intent contributed to institutional caution rather than alarm.

Late in 2046, joint reviews found common features across unrelated anomalies. Analysts proposed an external human system beyond Earth government control. Senior officials kept this theory inside restricted review groups.

The External Anomalies Phase concluded in early 2047, when accumulated evidence reached a threshold at which continued compartmentalisation was no longer tenable. The question confronting Earth institutions was no longer whether the anomalies were real, but whether they could plausibly be explained without reference to an external organising entity. This shift marked the transition toward direct investigation and eventual first contact.
